is there a more functional equivalent for specially "executing" the promises?
so similar to promise.allsettled, but specially. ok, seems weird, but i need to serialize execution.
you can't control the order in which code within a promise executed... so it's not just weird but also not really fully baked.
when a function yields control of the thread of execution, ultimately to the event loop, events dictate which routine is resumed;  waiting for a particular promise just yields.
(this is a form of cooperative multithreading, in case that helps you to think about it)
if you're not yielding within those functions, the promises will come back already resolved and the order in which you yield won't matter
it i found
so i guess there is no built function like threadpool in cava.

not as far as i know, though depending on the environment and what your treading requirements are it can be easy to build one... but keep in mind that you'll be passing around closure, not promises (since if you passed around a promise, it would already be executing and you would only get to wait once it yielded)
(that is, you must think of cooperative multithreading, not pre-empire multithreading)
